I have tried to contact the building manager to get it fixed up. He told me that there was a ticket placed, but when I checked the status I am not seeing one. This is very frustrating because I need my own internet. I am currently connected to the msoe one in my apartment. Even though this is internet, I bought a new router thinking my previous one failed on me. I don't want that to go to waste and also want a solid and reliable internet. Therefore, please try to fix this as soon as possible. You have access to the room. I have been waiting for too long to get this fixed. helpdesk-ticket.subject: Color Printing in the Library
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hi IT,
We just had a student in trying to print in color. I showed him how to select auto color in the printer options. He was printing 1 copy of the document (I think it was a total of 2 pages). He then scanned his ID at the color printer. Several pages were printed, but none were in color. I asked if he had other jobs he had sent to the printer and he said he did not. Could the color printer be looked at?
Thanks,
Denise Gergetz Librarian L-201 414-277-7182

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Denise Gergetz, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4225
We tested the printer on the weekend and it seems to be working correctly. The issue that the student was having with color printing might be tied to his computer instead of the printer. We have had no other reports of a issue with the color printer as of late. Hi Tara Caldwell,
After reviewing this ticket thoroughly, I found that Aaron wont be able to create his MSOE Alumni Account until he has met all of the undergraduate requirements. When Registrars has inputted into the system that he has his everything for his degree, the system will update, making him eligible to create the alumni email here at this link: https://gapps.msoe.edu/alumni/
Best regards, Sam West MSOE IT - Assistant Systems Administrator Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4247

Thank You,

Copy and paste the class roster from the my.msoe email and paste it into Outlook or Black Board and send email from there. This continues to leverage the up to date rosters from my.msoe but works around the email problem with a manual step.

I appreciate your patience and your time.

helpdesk-note.body:
Any outgoing email server must follow these rules: *Must come from an MSOE IP address *Must be a static IP address, no dynamic addresses are allowed *Must point to relay.msoe.edu and be added to the relay whitelist *Must have an MSOE faculty/staff as admin responsible for the account
Provided we can assign a static IP address to the device that will be sending the emails, this request is approved. Only one device will be authorized to act as a relay for this email account. I'd recommend a new email address (not ops@msoe.edu based on the generic nature of access) be used for this request.
If the intent is to have an account that monitors a large number of devices, I would recommend using an outside mail server not associated with MSOE mail servers.
Paul Fabian
MSOE Director of IT Services
fabian@msoe.edu
(414) 277-2355

Any outgoing email server must follow these rules:
*Must come from an MSOE IP address
*Must be a static IP address, no dynamic addresses are allowed

Provided we can assign a static IP address to the device that will be sending the emails, this request is approved. Only one device will be authorized to act as a relay for this email account. I'd recommend a new email address (not ops@msoe.edu based on the generic nature of access) be used for this request.

If the intent is to have an account that monitors a large number of devices, I would recommend using an outside mail server not associated with MSOE mail servers.

helpdesk-note.body:
Eric,
In effort to reduce the amount of outgoing spam we do not give direct access to our SMTP servers. Any outgoing email that is not coming from person (such as a printer or software) must get routed through our relay server. The device sending the email must get its IP address whitelisted on the relay server and it must be a static IP address. The IP address you provided is a dynamic IP address. We can assign it a static IP address but I want to confirm that the hostname of the computer is msoe-rpc-zxcv. Is that correct? Once we set the static IP address that computer will be the only one that will be able to send out the emails.
Thank You Mike Timm Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4292

On Wed, 13 Jan at 10:07 am , schmalzs <schmalzs@msoe.edu> wrote:
Mike Timm,

That should be sufficient. The host name you have listed is correct for the computer we would want this to work on. 

Thanks,

Scott Schmalz

P.S. Please let me know if there is anything else I will need to do on my end to get this setup. I assume I'll have to at the very least restart the computer. 

On Jan 13, 2016, at 10:00 AM, helpdesk <helpdesk@msoe.edu> wrote:

Eric,

In effort to reduce the amount of outgoing spam we do not give direct access to our SMTP servers. Any outgoing email that is not coming from person (such as a printer or software) must get routed through our relay server. The device sending the email must get its IP address whitelisted on the relay server and it must be a static IP address.

The IP address you provided is a dynamic IP address. We can assign it a static IP address but I want to confirm that the hostname of the computer is msoe-rpc-zxcv. Is that correct? Once we set the static IP address that computer will be the only one that will be able to send out the emails.

Thank You
Mike Timm

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4292

On Thu, 7 Jan at 12:36 pm , schmalzs <schmalzs@msoe.edu> wrote:
The IP address of the computer shouldn't make any difference. The way that the software (Stratasys Control Center) is setup is that the program can be opened on any computer on the network and connected to the machine. Then this computer needs to stay on and with Control Center open in order to email notifications.

This is what the setup screen looks like in Control Center. All I need is SMTP Server and an email address on the system to send notifications from. Then I can setup as many as 100 email recipients for as many as 100 systems/machines.

So I don't think you need this but the main computer that we are using in my lab has an IP Address of:  155.92.35.66, Subnet Mask:  255.255.255.0

Let me know if you have further questions,

helpdesk-ticket.description:

I need a video camera for an undergraduate research experiment later this quarter. I checked with the library about video camera rental and they said to get in touch with IT. Do you rent/loan video cameras for undergraduate use?
Thank you, Matt Bissen
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hello,
 
I need a video camera for an undergraduate research experiment later this quarter.  I checked with the library about video camera rental and they said to get in touch with IT.  Do you rent/loan video cameras for undergraduate use?
 
Thank you,
Matt Bissen

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Matthew, I only have three SONY cameras (and tripods) here for occasional uses like these. However, if you also have a smart phone, you will probably have a pretty high quality video as well. The challenge is that SONY uses a slightly smaller SD card than what your computer uses, so you will also need an adaptor/card reader for this if you were to do editing. You are welcome to come by and check it out at my office CC307. Pat Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4326

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Jobs broken between Jenzabar and CSGold that need fixing
helpdesk-ticket.description:
I have the following jobs that need to be reconnected to new Jenzabar:
Papercut printing: SQL that builds a file of ID numbers with Proximity number for Jenzabar table; then job runs to put this information on print server for MSOE people to use their ID card for printing.
Sportstracker: SQL from Jenzabar for Athletes to add access to CSGold patron groups. This works for two jobs; one to add access; the other to take away access when the athlete is updated to a non-access code in Sportstracker table.
Bookslips: SQL to add plan 80 to patrons in CSGold for those registered. This happens about 2 weeks before end of quarter through Tuesday of 2nd week of quarter. There is also a SQL that pulls transactions from CSGold and puts them in a Jenzabar Transaction history table for import onto Student accounts.
New Student Accounts: SQL when there is a stage change in Admissions and file is sent to Registrar; there is also a file built for CSGold of new students to add to system for ID making.
Thanks for all the help.
Sheila Barber Campus Card Administrator Milwaukee School of Engineering 1025 N Broadway CC435 Milwaukee WI 53202 barber@msoe.edu<mailto:barber@msoe.edu> (414) 277-7460

helpdesk-ticket.description:
I think I just fell for a virus-installing scam.
1. Is the email below legitimate? If not, how do I clean my machine?
2. How can I distinguish the email below from a clever virus-installing scheme?
Here are the details:
I received an unsolicited email (below) from the IT department asking “all employees” to log in using a link provided in the email rather than following instructions through an official MSOE webpage.
I confirmed I was able to log in to email through the normal URLs http://outlook.com/owa/msoe.edu https://outlook.office365.com/owa/?realm=msoe.edu#path=/mail
Then, I went back to the URL provided in the (scam?) email below. It went to what LOOKS like the MSOE log-in page, except it says it needs to run an EXE to see if my browser is compliant. So I downloaded and ran this EXE. Then I wondered if I had just made a big mistake, so I killed https://idp.remotewebportal.com/pa/422/Compliance.exe, and hoped it had not already infected my computer.
Thanks, Dr. Yoder

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Dr. Yoder,
I do not believe that email is legitimate for a few different reasons. The first problem that the email is not sent by helpdesk@msoe.edu. Second, the formatting of the email is incorrect. All helpdesk emails always follow the same setup, with a specific letterhead and signature. With these in mind, following the provided link reveals another thing: the SSL certificate is different from that on the correct login page. Finally, I decided to test it, logging in with a made up username and no password, which allowed for me to log in. This is a well done phishing attempt, with the login screen perfectly targeting MSOE. I will forward this information up the chain so that we can look into this issue.
Keeping the email address and the formatting in mind is the easiest way to distinguish phishing from legitimate emails. At this time, I would recommend immediately changing your password and downloading and running Malwarebytes and AdwCleaner. The URLs for these are as follows:
https://downloads.malwarebytes.org/file/mbam_current/ http://www.bleepingcomputer.com/download/adwcleaner/dl/125/
Please let me know if you have any more questions.

I received an unsolicited email (below) from the IT department asking “all employees” to log in using a link provided in the email rather than following instructions through an official MSOE webpage. 
 
I confirmed I was able to log in to email through the normal URLs
http://outlook.com/owa/msoe.edu
https://outlook.office365.com/owa/?realm=msoe.edu#path=/mail

So I downloaded and ran this EXE.  Then I wondered if I had just made a big mistake, so I killed https://idp.remotewebportal.com/pa/422/Compliance.exe, and hoped it had not already infected my computer.
 
Thanks,
Dr. Yoder

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Prof. Gonwa, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4378 Virus Scanning software says it needs to be updated, but it does not update. Trend Micro is alerting that it needs to be updated but it will no longer be updated. Microsoft Security Essentials is the replacement for this product and the IT department is working on pushing this out. Your computer remains protected by the Trend Micro definitions that are running even though they are out of date. Please disregard this alert until we have completed the MSE project. I have left you a voicemail with this information as well. I am going to mark this incident as resolved with this information. If you have additional questions, please contact the Help Desk at 414.277.7288
Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi andersonm, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4382
Is the follow you printing the default printer on your machine? If not you need to set it so that it is, as Jenzabar prefers to use the default printer. To check the default printer setting please follow the steps provided below.
1) Open the start button 2) Click Devices and Printers 3) Now look at the printer labeled "Follow you printing on printers". If it is set as the default printer, it will have a green check mark on it. 4) If it does not have the green check mark, right click on the printer labeled "Follow you printing on printers" and select "set as default printer". The printer should now have a green check mark.
If you could please let us know if the printer was already set as the default as well as if this solved your problem, it would be much appreciated.
Thanks,
Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Outlook: Suggested Meetings Plug-in
helpdesk-ticket.description:
I just discovered that there are some bugs in the “Suggested Meetings Plug-in” for Outlook for Mac. I’m running the current version under our Office 365 subscription.
Dr. Gerrits just sent an email about the faculty council meeting on 1/15. In Outlook the plug-in allowed me to click to add the meeting to my calendar. Unfortunately, it made a few errors:
* Instead of just adding it to my calendar it generated an invitation to Dr. Gerrits and all full-time faculty (thankfully blocked by the server configuration). * Even though it clearly said the meeting was at noon, it created an appointment at 6 AM on my calendar.
Then, when I removed the erroneous 6 AM appointment from my calendar, it again emailed everyone saying that the meeting had been canceled.
I saw this happen on some fall events (other users / students sending cancellation notices for my events) and did not know the cause – now I see that it seems to be Outlook on Mac using the Suggested Meetings Plug-in, at least.
I disabled this plug-in for my account at Office365.com, but it is still appearing – perhaps it will take some time for disabling it to take effect.
Perhaps IT should consider disabling this plug-in for all of msoe.edu until Microsoft has the bugs worked out.
Thank You,
Dr. Eric Durant

helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Prof. Schwartz's Trend Micro is not functioning properly. It is described as not updating properly, and thus not functioning as it should. Details are not clear at this point.
She requested that one of the Red Cap workers assist her when going through the Science building tomorrow. S246

helpdesk-note.body: Trend Micro subscriptions will not be renewed. We are working with Microsoft to deploy System Center Endpoint Protection (SCEP) but due to the problems with the Dell blade servers in November and December, we are behind on deployment. In the meantime, Trend will not update signatures, but the current install will continue to operate on older signatures. Meanwhile, the firewall has both subscription based signatures and persistent threat detection, and prevents malicious inbound and outbound traffic from the network.
helpdesk-note.body-html: Trend Micro subscriptions will not be renewed. We are working with Microsoft to deploy System Center Endpoint Protection (SCEP) but due to the problems with the Dell blade servers in November and December, we are behind on deployment. In the meantime, Trend will not update signatures, but the current install will continue to operate on older signatures. helpdesk-note.body:
Hello Dr. Damm,
Good morning! Our System Admins were able to see that the cause of your lockouts is Outlook. This could be an Outlook app on your phone (or tablet) or it could be your outlook client on your computer. Also, if you have any other email accounts that pull emails from your msoe.edu email, that could be the issue.
Please go through all of your devices (especially anything that you might have used in the past to view emails), and make sure they have current credentials for their email applications. If you use Android this can be tricky. If you run into problems feel free to come to the Helpdesk and we will help you do this.
We realize this is frustrating and unfortunately this is a problem where we need you to help us help you.
Have a great day!

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi damm, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4495
I have included the instructions in order to change the password associated with outlook on you school machine.
1) Click the start button. 2) In the search bar, type Credential Manager 3) Open Credential Manager 4) Under the section labeled Generic credentials there should be a line of blue text that is formatted along the lines of "Outlook 15" followed by your username. Click the blue text. 5)The text should drop down, revealing an edit and remove from vault option. You will want to select remove from vault, and indicate that you are sure you wish to remove this credential. 6)Open outlook. It should prompt you for your new password.
I will be marking this resolved, however, if you have any additional questions or concerns please feel free to contact us.
Thanks,
Thomas Schleich helpdesk@msoe.edu 414-277-7288
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi damm,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/4495

I have included the instructions in order to change the password associated with outlook on you school machine.

1) Click the start button.
2) In the search bar, type Credential Manager
3) Open Credential Manager
4) Under the section labeled Generic credentials there should be a line of blue text that is formatted along the lines of "Outlook 15" followed by your username. Click the blue text.
5)The text should drop down, revealing an edit and remove from vault option. You will want to select remove from vault, and indicate that you are sure you wish to remove this credential.
6)Open outlook. It should prompt you for your new password.
